column5:
Laryngeal colouring

Likely the earliest traditionally dateable sound change in Carite, and in Indo-European in general, is laryngeal colouring. As its traces can be seen even across Anatolian, it is likely that an allophonic process of vowel colouring next to the traditionally posited laryngeals *h‚ÇÇ *h‚ÇÉ predates the Anatolian split. This had little effect on the morphology of Indo-European early on, and only later did it influence its grammatical ablaut. A generalised overview of the process:|-|Two things are notable about this change. The first is that, as in other Indo-European languages, the effects of laryngeal colouring are recoverable only for the vowel *e, and not any other vowel; whether this is due to its effect only on this vowel, or that the effects of colouring on other vowels were lost, is indeterminable. The second is that, after this change, we cannot reliably distinguish in Carite history the laryngeals *h‚ÇÅ and *h‚ÇÇ later in time; one theory states that might have merged at some point immediately after colouring effects took place, phonemicising the vowel colour, and another that they remained distinguished, but that sound changes treated them the same due to their phonetic and phonological similarity.
column9:
According to some, Carite also coloured *a next to *h‚ÇÉ:|-|According to those in favour, the colouring of *e next to two different colouring laryngeals can be predicted if the colouring was a two-step process; first, *h‚ÇÇ would colour *e to an *a, and this *a would be coloured to *o (alongside uncoloured *e) next to *h‚ÇÉ. However, this environment only appears to appear in a single word (being pie@h‚ÇÇeh‚ÇÉm√≥s, whence ¬∞OOMOS¬∞), which makes it likely another more mainstream explanation can be found.

It is worth noting that while the Latin and Greek reflexes of *h‚ÇÇo appear to be either /o/ or /a/, Carite appears to simply reflect *o for these cases.
column12:
Early cluster changes

Voicing assimilation in obstruent clusters is another extremely early Indo-European phenomenon. It predates all the other recoverable processes, and its age relative to laryngeal colouring cannot be determined. The process dictates the spread of voicing from the final element in a cluster regressively.
column14: This change also operated when the cluster included aspirates: they can be assumed to also be voiced, or breathily/partially voiced, to begin with. All aspirates in such clusters presumably become voiceless aspirates, but their result cannot be shown to be different from regular voiced obstruents: presumably, this aspiration is lost early enough internally to merge their outcome with that of regular tenues, and not (the somewhat later) voiceless aspirates.
column15:
This was later generalised to all aspirates before a plosive:|-|This assimilation happened both at morpheme boundaries, and morpheme-internally (especially when triggered by ablaut):

*ni-s·µíd-√≥s > ¬∞NIZDOS¬∞

The voiced consonants produced by this change were generally allophonic, only to phonemicise later when their morphophonological environment became irrecoverable.
column16: A somewhat later process, Siebs' Law, changed this system after the rise and proliferation of prefixed s-mobile. Word-initial clusters with |*sB *sB ∞|, formed morphologically, would devoice, possibly giving rise to a new set of voiceless aspirates, in addition to adding to a growing number of voiceless tenues:|-|It is not clear if the voiceless aspirates remained phonemic for long - in any case, in Carite, they behave identically to the regular voiceless tenues and presumably merged shortly after if they ever were distinct in the first place. Two other large, early processes involving /*s/ took place at roughly the same time.
column17: The first was the dissolution of thorn clusters which sets the late Common Indo-European group, together with Carite, apart from earlier Indo-European. In Carite, the thorn clusters underwent metathesis and deaffrication:|-|The reflex of |*T{g,«µ}( ∑) ∞| as [*{g,«µ}( ∑) ∞z] is actually expected, since the first part of the intermediate step cluster |*d ∞g( ∑) ∞| (after assimilation) is predictably deaspirated before a plosive, and is then affricated and metathesised.
column26: The degemination of dentals happened similarly to Greek; the first dental (i.e. alveolar plosive) was affricated, and then the resulting cluster was simplified:|-|This process probably only happened only at morpheme boundaries: the pie@√°tta was preserved seemingly unaltered. It is possible that the word had some other process at play, or that it was a babbled word or a loan common to Indo-European; regardless, the process continued to be a productive morphophonological alternation. Compare this to Italo-Celtic and Germanic, where the degemination of dentals resulted in *ss.
column28:
Osthoff's Law & Laryngeal deletions

Another early process in Carite history, shared with Italo-Celtic, Greek and probably Germanic, is Osthoff's Law, which dictates the shortening of sequences of long vowels followed by a resonant and another, indeterminate consonant:|-|Osthoff's sequences shortened both internally and finally, and‚Äîcrucial for dating the change‚Äîalso happened before laryngeals that were later lost. It is especially important in Carite, being an active surface filter for a greater length of time.
column29: The first big loss of laryngeals (first laryngeal loss) happened immediately after Osthoff's law took place. It dictated the loss of some interconsonantal laryngeals:|-|The inherited Indo-European sequences of the type *≈çRHC (including the diphthongs *≈çy *≈çw, and others) were already shortened and merged into sequences of the type *oRHC due to Osthoff's law. It is likely this loss of laryngeals may be dated back to common Proto-Indo-European as we appear to find its effects in all daughters.
column31:
Centumisation

Centumisation in Carite took place somewhat late, and only after the coalescence of a sequence of a back velar followed by *w into a single labiovelar consonant:|-|Some fringe linguists hypothesise that this change also affected the laryngeal sequence *h‚ÇÇw > *h‚ÇÉ, citing late-attested forms such as ?? (from *???) and ?? (hypothetically from *???, though this etymology is controversial). Others dismiss this assumption and claim that *h‚ÇÇ had by then merged already with *h‚ÇÅ and that it is indistinguishable from it in these contexts.
column34: Centumisation proper happened quite similarly to how it played out in Greek and Italo-Celtic: the merger of palatovelars into plain velars was straightforward and wasn't followed by any secondary, characteristically satem changes (cf. Germanic and RUKI). Centumisation is taken to have been a single, simple step:|-|Carite is peculiar in that it is possible to recover the identity of the palatovelar series before the labial *w, as they didn't coalesce into a labiovelar, and are instead preserved as *kw *k ∞w *gw *g ∞w. This is also present in Greek, which reflects initial *·∏±w as Œ∫œÖ- (ku-, as in grc@Œ∫œçœâŒΩ=k√∫≈çn 'dog', from pie@·∏±w·πì; other palatovelars analogously), and (with varying peculiarities) internal *·∏∞w as a geminate labiovelar instead of a short one (for example /-kk-/, as in Aeolian grc@·º¥Œ∫Œ∫ŒøœÇ=√≠kkos 'horse', from pie@h‚ÇÅ√©·∏±wos) .
column37: Immediately following centumisation was labiovelar dissimilation, where many new Carite labiovelars, plenty of which were sourced from coalescent mergers, dissimilated at a distance. Namely, two consecutive syllables were disallowed to have labiovelars in their onsets, forcing a dissimilative loss of rounding:
column38:
Laryngeal and syllabic sonorant development

It was roughly at this point that everyone can agree with the first merger of laryngeals, where *h‚ÇÅ merged with *h‚ÇÇ. It is assumed the direction of the merger was *h‚ÇÅ > *h‚ÇÇ due to the colouring effect the merged laryngeal had on sonorants shortly thereafter. Some linguists prefer calling the laryngeals *h‚Çê *h‚Çí from this point onwards, referring to their colouring effects, but this usage is not adopted here.
column39: At roughly the same time, the first loss of laryngeals occurred:|-|It is worth noting that when this sonorant was followed by another consonant, the newly lengthened vowel was subsequently shortened again through Osthoff's Law.
column40: One of the changes that lead to the distinguishing of Carite from its now diverging cousins is the vocalisation of sonorants that worked in several stages. Unlike Germanic, where syllabic sonorants simply ejected an *u before them, Carite syllabic sonorants interacted extensively with adjacent laryngeals in a fashion not unlike Greek and Latin. The first to be vocalised were sonorants next to a laryngeal:
column46: Next, an epenthetic vowel was inserted to take up the syllabicity of any remaining sonorant. Where exactly this sound was inserted, if the sonorant was remained and if the vowel was a schwa Indogermanicum depended on the environment:|-|It is likely the reflex of nasals in this particular environment started of as a nasalised neutral vowel, i.e. *…ôÃÉ, which later lost its nasalisation and neutralised differently than its oral equivalent.
column49: The same schwa was inserted after an interconsonantal laryngeal surrounded by true consonants:
column50: This schwa took up rounding from any previous consonant, though *w curiously enough did not appear to take part in this process, possibly due to its semivocalic nature:
column52: Due to the regressive action of the boukolos rule, which delabialised labiovelars next to *u, this delabialised any labiovelar after which it occured:|-|Carite does not seem to reflect the progressive version of this law that well, or‚Äîaccording to some‚Äîat all.
column53: The schwa took colour from the previous laryngeal much like older *e:
column55: The schwa also picked up rounding from a following *m, but not any other labial:|-|Notably, this rule postdates the colouring of post-laryngeal schwas as the coloured schwas did not become a high vowel, and instead merged with the older mid vowels.
column56: Finally, it lost its distinctiveness by becoming a generic unrounded high vowel:
column57: It is likely that at this point the laryngeals lost differentiation and merged into one general laryngeal continuant, completing the second merger of laryngeals:
column58: The next loss of laryngeals (second laryngeal loss) happened to sequences of vowels with a laryngeal:|-|The lengthening of contracted laryngeal sequences still obeyed Osthoff's Law, shortening the new vowels when followed by a resonant and then an obstruent. Examples of this process are scant, but evident in the so-called conjunctive nominals, which, in early Carite, take special forms in subordinated clauses and in coordinated clauses; a typical example of this is the masculine noun ¬∞EKWOS¬∞, its genitive plural attested both as the regular ekw≈çm and in the conjunctive form ekwomfe; the length of the vowel in the suffix is indicative of Osthoff's Law. With the deletion of the laryngeal and subsequent compensatory lengthening, any allophonous colouring effects were phonemicised. It is worth noting that Dybo's Law, which was responsible for pretonic shortening after the loss of laryngeals in Italo-Celtic and Germanic, did not affect Carite.
column60:
Engels' Law

An unusual, but well-documented Carite change is the effect of laryngeals on consonants in word-initial position. They voiced obstruents and fortified semivowels, probably through a process of glottalisation:|-|A longstanding hypothesis is that the fortition of *Hy resulted in *·∏±, which was still unmerged, but otherwise invisible to historical linguistics. This opinion is somewhat controversial, but unfalsifiable due to our inability to elucidate which exact allophone *y fortited to. This change is occasionally termed Engels' Law, and it was first posited by the Limburgish philologist Klaus Engels.
column67: After this, the laryngeals fail to effect any further changes, and are likely lost shortly thereafter, completing the third laryngeal loss:|-|This included all word-initial laryngeals immediately followed by a consonant, which were lost in all daughters except for Anatolian, Greek, Armenian and Phrygian. It is worth noting this change phonemicised what used to be allophones, i.e. the colouring of *e and Engels' Law.
column68:
Consonant developments

Word-initial laryngeal voicing of *s enables the dating of another change, its word-initial debuccalisation which is partially shared with Greek, where it prevocalically, even if not word-initial:
column69: This change was probably concurrent with the deaspiration of obstruents after nasals:
column70: Another concurrent change was the debuccalisation of word-initial prevocalic *g ∞:|-|It is probable that this change would also have affected word-initial *g ∑ ∞ ‚Üí *…¶ ∑, but the labiovelarisation of its rounding probably reverted the change shortly thereafter, putting it at ‚Üí *g ∑ ∞ again.
column71: The collapse of the three-way contrast system followed shortly thereafter. The aspiration feature of voiced aspirates would combine with their voicing to produce a breathy phonation, which merged with voiceless tenues. A possible glottalic interpretation is that in these early Carite stages voicing was a creaky or glottalised feature (explaining laryngeal voicing of word-initial obstruents), and that breathy segments had more in common acoustically with voiceless tenues. Regardless, the internal history of this change is opaque, and we only posit:|-|Notably, this change did not affect word-initial *h derived from older *g ∞, as it had already merged with the reflex of initial *s, but did affect all internal instances of *g ∞‚Äîeven those that were preserved as a result of prefixation. It is worth noting that the devoicing of Proto-Indo-European's voiced aspirates is shared with Latin (before becoming fricatives shortly after) and Greek (although unlike them, Carite loses the aspiration) while they are contrastively voiced in Celtic (where they merge into *b) and Germanic (where they remain distinct as part of Grimm's Law).
column75: Long-distance assimilation of labial *p into a following *k ∑ likely happened around this time:|-|While similar to the assimilation we may find in both Italic and Celtic, although individual developments, the Carite rule additionally requires the second labiovelar to be prevocalic.
column76: It was roughly at this time that the more lenis labiovelar plosives *k ∑ *g ∑ lost their velar plosion, but retained the lower frequency timbre of velarisation by labiodentalising instead of merely shifting to labials:|-|While the change of *g ∑ to *v may at first sight be erroneously compared to the Latin shift of *g ∑ into <> [w], it is worth noting that the sound in Latin was an approximant and would correspond to ¬ßlang_0 *w. Latin retains its *k ∑ as <> (ignoring unrelated unrounding developments) while Greek merges all labiovelars into labials or dentals, depending on the environment and dialect.
column78:
Diphthong collapse

When any vowel was followed by *i *u, the sequence collapsed into a diphthong with *i *u surfacing as the semivowels *y *w. If they were formerly stressed, the stress shifted to the preceding vowel.
column80: The homorganic vowel-sonorant sequences *eye coalesced into a long vowel:
column81:
This coalescence was the first part of a more prevalent collapse of certain homosyllabic diphthongs:|-|Notably, the collapse didn't affect sequences like *yV, nor the high vowels resulting from a laryngeal schwa. Osthoff's Law was clearly still productive at this stage, with e.g. pie@sw√©ydoh‚ÇÇ first becoming *s√©yd≈ç as the resulting *ƒì was shortened before predictably becoming ¬∞SWEYDOO¬∞.

We may find similarities with other branches where some diphthongs underwent an identical or similar process. For example, *ow surfaces as ≈´ in Latin, just as it did in Carite (although *ew had merged into *ow prior to this). The collapse of *ey into *ƒ´ is shared with Germanic and Latin (while Celtic collapses it into *ƒì) and *oy merges into ≈´ in Latin (but also ƒ´ in some environments or, rarely, retained as <>).
column94:
Other minor changes

A few other consonant changes date to roughly this period, without an easy way to date them with precision relative to the rest of Carite developments of this time:|-|Some are shared with sister branches, such as the fortition of *m word-initially before liquids with Latin and Greek.
column103: Somewhere around this time, the short high vowels *i *u turned into glides when unstressed and preceding another vowel:|-|This does not appear to have taken place when following any cluster.
column105: Following the reduction of these unstressed high vowels, a minor palatalisation took place:|-|This assibilation of dentals resembles Greek, but is by no means as widespread as it is there.
column107: This was likely concurrent with this change pertaining to vowel length:
column108: Stressed *ƒì *≈ç were raised in stressed syllables:
column112: A surface filter of nasal assimilation that applied across Carite history is also dated to have started up to this point in time:|-|It is worth noting that *m did not appear to assimilate into *n before *n, which was retained as the sequence *mn instead.
column114:
Carite Verner's Law

The change that is taken to define Carite as a fully independent language in its own ecosystem is the Carite Verner's Law, a structural parallel of Verner's Law in Germanic. Onsets of stressed, non-initial Carite syllables were voiced, and when the distinctive position of accent was lost to a word-initial accent relocation, the voicing phonemicised completely:|-|The voicing is likely to initially have affected only the onset of the stressed syllable that caused it, but voicing assimilation rules for clusters spread the voicing to the whole cluster. It is worth noting that, despite the name and similar effect - that is, the voicing of segments based on now-lost stress - this law significantly differed from its Germanic equivalent regardless. In Germanic, clusters were automatically disqualified from being affected by the law and the requirement was that the preceding syllable nucleus was unstressed. In Carite, clusters benefited significantly from the effects of this law and it only affected the onset of what was formerly a stressed syllable, as long as it was non-initial; as such, word-final coda voicing effects as in Germanic's *-az suffix (from *-os) are nowhere to be found in Carite.

Minor consonant changes

Word-initial /w/, which only appeared before liquids or vowels, either fortited into /b/ or lenited into /h/, respectively:

Vowel developments

A short, unstressed vowel is deleted when directly preceding a long vowel.

However, analogy must have occurred at some point after this, with the stem that underwent the gemination being generalised.

Some reconstruct an actual change, others find this distinction rather meaningless. Nonetheless, it is presented here:

column156:
Lef√®vre's Law

Interaction between dental plosives and liquids resulted in a chain shift which is, even today, not entirely well understood. Dental fricatives fortited into plosives before rhotics, which may have triggered a subsequent shift of old /tr/ and /dr/ to /tl/ and /dl/; in turn, old /tl/ and /dl/ dissimilated into /kl/ and /gl/. No counterexamples to these changes may be found. This chain shift is often referred to as Lef√®vre's Law.
column162: The remaining dental fricative /Œ∏/ only occurred word-finally after nasalised vowels, resulting from the old *-ns we saw before. For this reason, many believe that this fricative was never truly dental and had always been [s].
column164: Word-final /h/ was lost, triggering compensatory lengthening:
column166: /ps/ appears to dissimilate to /ks/:|-|While limited to two nominals, this change is particularly important in the formation of future stems of thematics and was morphologised. This change also notably phonemicises previous allophonic instances of [hs].
column167: Carite later underwent some form of liquid metathesis, more specifically in LV sequences, although this only occurred in specific conditions. First of all, the liquid must be preceded by a plosive. Secondly, the vowel needs to be short. Finally, the metathesis did not occur if the vowel was followed by a liquid or /h/ in the coda or if the sequence was word-final:

column170: If they were ever distinct, the following diphthongs collapsed into long vowels:

I-umlaut

A process similar to the Germanic i-umlaut and, as such, often referred to in a similar manner, took place. More specifically, the vowels *a *o *u, no matter their length, were fronted to *√¶ *√∏ *y when preceding a syllable with *j in its onset or *i *e as its nucleus. This also affected diphthongs where the second element was *i:|-|While this also significantly increased the occurrence of *√∏ *y, which were otherwise relatively marginal vowels, it also gave birth to [√¶], a new allophone of *a in the aforementioned environments.

A-umlaut

It is easily provable that this process took place after i-umlaut, as the raised [√¶] did not lower the high vowels.

column196:
Vowel Harmony

A major change that would also cause lasting morphological effects was the widespread vowel harmony that occurred around the beginning of the second century. Only stressed vowels retained the full eight-vowel distinction, with unstressed vowels being limited to *a *i *u. This excluded diphthongs and *e‚ÇÇ *o‚ÇÇ.
column198: Furthermore, *e‚ÇÇ *o‚ÇÇ merged into *e *o when stressed, but reverted to their previous *i *u in unstressed positions:

Carite Exon's Law

Similar to its equivalent in Latin, syncope took place in a medial sequence of two light syllables. Unlike Latin, however, which deleted the vowel in the former syllable, Old Carite underwent syncope in the latter syllable.

At some point in Old Carite history, stress shifted from being predictably word-initial to being predictably penultimate. Several changes, presumably taking place towards the end of Old Carite times, clearly show traces of such a stress system. For example, long, stressed word-initial vowels broke into a palatal glide and the original vowel:
